{[%evp 0,52,16,28,38,38,18,15,13,-27,-27,-61,-19,-53,-18,-14,-1,-45,-45,-20,-3,
17,10,-16,-12,3,13,1,19,12,15,28,29,-7,5,2,6,6,74,13,44,22,21,30,30,29,45,37,
37,14,22,-26,-25,-36,-50]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d3 {This modest-looking move isn't
without venom. Since the e4-pawn is currently covered, White can safely
transfer his knight on g3 without retreating his light-squared bishop. On the
other hand, Black also has more activity than in main lines of Breyer.
Starting from 1950'es, this move was seen in practice of many great players
including Tal, Stein, Bronstein and more.} Nbd7 ({It is possible to switch to
Chigorin paths with} 10... c5 11. Nbd2 Nc6 12. Nf1 Be6 13. Ng3 {Black is very
solid, but White's chances seem preferable.}) 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Nf1 Nc5 $1 {
This way of delaying d3-d4 was proved to be most effective.} (12... Re8 {
runs into} 13. Ng5 $1 ({Instead,} 13. Ng3 Nc5 14. Bc2 Bf8 {transposes to text.}
) 13... d5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Qh5 Bxg5 16. Bxg5 {, and the powerful bishops
provide White with some initiative.}) ({Dubious is} 12... c5 $6 13. Ng3 Re8 {
White's attacking potential is well illustrated after} 14. Nf5 Bf8 15. Ng5 d5
16. exd5 Bxd5 $2 ({The lesser evil is} 16... Nb6 17. c4 $16) 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18.
Qh5 $18 {, and Black's position collapses.}) 13. Bc2 Re8 {The standard Breyer
setup is almost completed.} 14. Ng3 {The most consistent. White insists on
d3-d4 advance, while his knight might be hosted on f5.} ({The alternative plan
is} 14. Ne3 Bf8 15. b4 Ncd7 ({Possible is also} 15... Ne6 16. c4 g6 17. Bb2 Bg7
18. a4 bxc4 19. Nxc4 {This position was reached in Tal, M - Furman, S Baku 1972
Now Black should have played} Rb8 $1 $146 20. Rb1 Nh5 {, obtaining a decent
counter-play.}) 16. Bb3 {, fighting for the control of d5 seems somewhat slow
and can be met by} c6 $1 17. a4 d5 18. Bd2 h6 {Black had no problems in Sax, G
- De Vreugt, D Bolzano 1999}) (14. b4 Ncd7 {mostly leads to the same.}) 14...
Bf8 15. b4 {The most common. White starts to expand on the queenside and
reduces Black's pressure on e4.} (15. Be3 Ncd7 16. Bb3 {, as in Palac, M -
Kuljasevic, D Plitvicka Jezera 2013 can be naturally met by} h6 $146 17. Nf5 d5
18. Nd2 dxe4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. dxe4 Nf6 $11) ({The more ambitious alternative
is} 15. Nh2 {, intending to push f2-f4} d5 $1 {Of course, this thematic break
comes on time.} 16. Qf3 ({Harmless is} 16. Ng4 Nxg4 17. Qxg4 {This position
was reached in Vachier Lagrave, M - Solomon, K Istanbul 2012 Now I like the
following way of handling the position:} Qf6 $146 18. b4 Na4 19. Bd2 Qg6 {
Black's king is safe, so there are no problems.}) 16... Ne6 {The knight made
its job on c5, so it comes closer to the king to take part in the defence.} 17. Nf5
Kh8 $1 18. h4 ({Hardly better is} 18. Ng4 Nxg4 19. Qxg4 c5 20. h4 {,as in
Shamkovich, L-O'Kelly de Galway, A Palma de Mallorca 1966 At this moment Black
has no reason for rejecting the natural} g6 $146 21. Nh6 Qc7 $15) 18... c5 {
Black starts the usual expansion on the queenside, so White has to act fast on
the opposite side.} 19. Bg5 Nxg5 20. hxg5 Ng8 {The knight temporarily moves
back in order to secure the king.} 21. Qg3 g6 22. Ne3 d4 {Black had better
chances due to his space advantage in Browne, W - Portisch, L Wijk aan Zee 1972})
15... Ne6 (15... Ncd7 $5 {is another solid continuation, but the text looks
more active.}) 16. d4 ({Less ambitious is} 16. a4 c5 17. bxc5 Nxc5 18. axb5
axb5 19. Bg5 {This was Berg, E - Thomassen, J Caleta 2011 Now correct was} h6
$146 20. Rxa8 Bxa8 21. Be3 Qc7 {, and Black is fine.}) 16... a5 $1 {For some
reason, this natural move was seen only in one human game. At the same time,
it definitely makes sense to underline the structural drawbacks of opponent's
queenside.} (16... exd4 17. cxd4 d5 18. e5 Ne4 {is what Black played in most games, but this doesn't look safe. For instance,} 19. Rb1 g6 20. Nxe4 dxe4
21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Qd5 23. Re2 {Black had no adequate play for the pawn in
Ivanchuk,V - Southam,T Adelaide 1988}) 17. bxa5 ({The premature exchange} 17.
dxe5 $6 dxe5 {might put White under pressure since the b4-pawn is weak. For
instance,} 18. Bd2 axb4 19. cxb4 Ra3 20. Bb3 c5 $1 {Black takes over the
initiative.}) ({White achieves nothing special also after} 17. d5 Nf4 18. Ne2
Ng6 $132 {, and the c7-c6 break is to follow.}) 17... Rxa5 18. Bd2 ({In case of} 
18. dxe5 $6 dxe5 19. Nxe5 Qxd1 20. Bxd1 Nc5 {Black regains the pawn and
obtains a clear positional advantage.}) 18... Qa8 19. Qb1 {We have been
following the game Renet, O - Van der Wiel, J Lyon 1990} ({After} 19. dxe5 dxe5
20. Nxe5 Rxa2 21. Rxa2 Qxa2 22. Bb3 Qa6 23. Nh5 Nxh5 24. Qxh5 Re7 {Black has
nothing to worry about.}) {Now I suggest the following natural way fo handling
the position:} 19... Qa7 $146 20. Be3 ({In case of} 20. Nf5 Ra8 21. dxe5 dxe5
22. Be3 Qa6 23. Nxe5 Rxa2 24. Rxa2 Qxa2 $132 {Black has enough counterplay
along the a-file.}) 20... c5 21. dxe5 (21. d5 Nf4 {feels more comfortable for
Black.}) 21... dxe5 22. Nxe5 Bd6 {Now White cannot avoid the damage of his
pawn structure.} (22... g6 $5 {also seems to offer Black long-lasting
compensation.}) 23. Nf3 Bxg3 24. fxg3 h6 25. Nh4 Qb8 26. Nf5 Qe5 {The active
piece play and pressure on e4 gives Black full compensation for the pawn.} *

