{[%evp 0,58,28,42,14,14,15,17,17,-27,-30,0,9,-17,-1,9,16,-20,-22,-22,14,1,-7,
-18,17,12,-7,-3,14,4,3,7,17,20,20,20,36,40,40,26,27,8,27,-3,52,55,72,0,0,-6,15,
40,24,30,44,39,40,38,39,36,41]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. c4 {This
aggressive move was successfully introduced by one of greatest players in the
past Efim Geller. In comparison to 11.Nbd2, White has more control over the
centre, while the dark-squared bishop remains active. On the flipside, White
delays his development and reduces the control of d4.} c6 $1 {This
prophylactic move makes it impossible for White's knight to follow with d4-d5.}
({The merits of White's setup are well illustrated in the following cases:} 
11... c5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Nc3 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 b4 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17.
cxd5 {White was clearly better due to the strong d5-passer and eventually won
in Zhigalko,S - Rzayev,B Baku 2012.}) ({Let me also share the following
classical game, where the timid} 11... Bb7 $6 {was nicely refuted:} 12. Nc3 c6
({Hardly better is} 12... b4 13. Nd5 a5 14. a3 c6 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Nh4 $1 {
Durarbayli,V - Lkhagvasuren,T Ulaanbaatar MGL 2018}) 13. a3 $1 {White
reasonably doesn't hurry - now Black's setup is rather passive, so it's
possible to spend one tempo in order to secure the c3-knight.} Qc7 14. Bg5 Rae8
15. Rc1 Qb8 16. Ba2 $1 {White starts to slowly squeeze the opponent's setup on
the queenside.} Kh8 {This move illustrates well, that Black's position lacks
any counter-attacking ideas.} (16... exd4 17. Nxd4 bxc4 18. Bxc4 $16 {is just
positionally bad - there are few obvious weaknesses.}) 17. b4 c5 (17... Bd8 18.
c5 {is not a fun, so Spassky invites unfavorable complications.}) 18. bxc5 exd4
19. c6 $1 dxc3 (19... Bxc6 20. Nxd4 {just drops a pawn.}) 20. cxb7 Qxb7 21.
cxb5 Qxb5 22. Rxc3 {White was much better and eventually won in Geller,
E-Spassky,B Riga 1958 URS-ch}) 12. Nc3 b4 $1 {The most challenging response -
Black seizes a lot of space on the queenside and weakens the e4-pawn.} (12...
Bb7 $6 13. a3 {takes us back to above-mentioned game Geller - Spassky.}) 13.
Na4 {The knight is stuck on the side of the board now, but White has a
long-term plan of developing his play on the queenside.} (13. Ne2 $5 {This
pawn sacrifice recently has gained some popularity} Nxe4 $1 {Bravely accepting
the challenge. Indeed, liquidating the central pawn is a certain achievement
for Black in Ruy Lopez.} ({In case of} 13... c5 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Ng3 Bb7 16.
Qc2 Re8 17. a3 a5 18. Ba4 {Black fails to transfer his knight to d4, whereas
the weakness of d5-spot starts to tell.}) 14. Qc2 Nef6 (14... f5 {is the most
popular by far, but I don't really trust it} 15. c5+ d5 ({After} 15... Kh8 16.
cxd6 Bxd6 17. Be3 {White had more than sufficient compensation for the pawn
in Kantans, T - Oparin, G Batumi GEO 2018}) 16. Be3 $1 Kh8 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. dxe5
Bh4 {Since Black's pawn structure is fragile, he is looking for an activity on
the kingside. However, as the following game shows, White shouldn't fear
ghosts and play} 19. g3 $1 Bg5 20. Bxg5 Qxg5 21. h4 Qe7 22. f3 Qxc5+ $6 ({
Better was} 22... Nxc5 23. Rac1 Ne6 24. Qxc6 Bb7 25. Qd6 {, but even then
Black wouldn't be safe since White's rooks would penetrate into his camp soon.
}) 23. Qxc5 Nxc5 24. Nd4 f4 25. g4 $16 {Black had a poor pawn structure in
Grandelius,N - Amin,B Sharjah UAE 2018}) 15. Ng3 {The knight heads on f5 and
unlocks the way for the rook.} (15. c5 $5 {was never seen in practice yet,
though it definitely looks in the spirit of White's previous aggressive play.
The play might continue:} e4 16. cxd6 Bxd6 17. Ng5 Nb6 18. Qxc6 Bf5 {This
position is full of tactics and offers interesting dynamic play for both sides.
}) 15... c5 ({The greedy} 15... exd4 $2 16. Nxd4 Ne5 17. Bf4 {offers White a
powerful initiative.}) 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. Rxe5 {White regained
the pawn, but the vulnerable rook gives Black an important tempo for
consolidating.} Bd6 19. Re2 Qc7 20. Nf5 {The most ambitious try.} (20. Bg5 {
is well met by} Be5 $1 ({Instead,} 20... Bxg3 21. fxg3 Qxg3 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23.
Rf1 {left Black with an exposed king in Arjun, K - Maiorov, N Roquetas de Mar
ESP 2019}) 21. Rae1 Bd4 22. Nf5 Bxf5 23. Qxf5 Qc6 $1 $11 {The strong d4-bishop
fully compensates for White's bishops pair.}) 20... Be5 21. Bg5 h6 22. Bh4 Bxf5
23. Qxf5 Rae8 24. Rae1 {Visually, the pressure along e-file looks annoying.
However, Black's next few precise moves force favourable simplifications:} g6 $1
25. Qf3 g5 26. Bg3 Bxg3 27. Qxf6 Rxe2 28. Rxe2 Qf4 29. Qe7 {The only way to
maintain the tension and cover the back-rank.} Qd4 30. Kf1 {We have been
following the game Christiansen, J - Tarjan, J Douglas ENG 2018 At this moment
Black should have played} Bd6 31. Qd7 Qf6 32. Qc6 a5 {,achieving full
equality.}) 13... c5 14. d5 {This advance secures a typical space advantage,
a-la King's Indian. There are no weaknesses in Black's camp, but it's not easy
to find good spots for all the minor pieces. Therefore, his next move looks
very natural.} ({Dubious is} 14. dxc5 $6 dxc5 15. Bc2 Qc7 16. b3 Nb8 $1 17. Qe2
Nc6 $15 {Black was first to take control over the central spot in Shabalov, A -
Kaufman,L Arlington 2010}) 14... Re8 $1 {Now f8 is vacant for the knight,
while the light-squared bishop can be located on d7.} 15. Bc2 Nf8 16. b3 {
As was mentioned before, White is able to liberate the knight. Moreover, he is
getting ready for opening the a-file.} Ng6 17. Nb2 Bd7 18. a3 a5 19. Ra2 h6 20.
Be3 {White is ready to double his rooks along the a-file. If Black doesn't
want to sit and wait, he has to develop his counterplay quickly.} Nh7 21. Qd2 {
The most natural.} ({One correspondence game saw} 21. Qe2 Qc8 22. Rea1 Qb7 23.
Nd3 Reb8 24. Qe1 Qc8 25. Bd1 f5 {Black had enough counterplay.}) 21... Ng5 22.
Nxg5 Bxg5 23. axb4 {A premature exchange.} ({In case of} 23. Rea1 Bxe3 24. Qxe3
Rb8 25. axb4 axb4 26. Ra7 Nf4 27. Nd3 Qg5 28. Nxf4 exf4 29. Qf3 Qe5 {the
control over e5-spot compensates for the activity of White's rooks. However,
it would be still a better choice.}) 23... Bxe3 24. Qxe3 axb4 25. Rea1 Rxa2 26.
Rxa2 Nf4 27. Nd3 Qg5 28. Nxf4 exf4 29. Qd3 Qe5 {White's play on the queenside
came to an end. He was doomed to passive defence and eventually lost in
Vallejo Pons,F - Carlsen,M Berlin 2015} *

