} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. c4 c6 12. a3 {White secures a nice spot for his
knight, but leaving the pieces on their initial spots is connected with a
definite risk.} (12. Be3 {A rare move, that was only seen in 2 games so far.
As usual, it locks the e-file, so the e4-pawn is getting vulnerable.} bxc4 ({
The main tactical point behind White's last move is} 12... Nxe4 13. cxb5 axb5
14. Qc2 Nef6 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Qxc6 $14 {, regaining the pawn and putting
Black under definite pressure.}) ({Too passive is} 12... Bb7 13. Nbd2 c5 14. d5
Nb6 15. Qc2 Bc8 16. a4 $14 {Adhiban,B - Amin,B Sharjah UAE 2018}) 13. Bxc4 Nxe4
14. Qc2 ({In case of} 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Nd2 Nf6 17. Qc2 Nd5 {
White has an obvious compensation due to the better pawn structure, but Black
doesn't have problems here.}) 14... Ng5 ({Less precise is} 14... Nef6 15. dxe5
Nxe5 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Nc3 Nd5 18. Rad1 {White had interesting compensation
for the pawn in Mosadeghpour, M - Matinian, N Hamedan IRI 2018}) 15. Bxg5 Bxg5
16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. Nc3 {White's lead in development makes it
possible to regain the pawn} g6 19. Rxe5 Bf5 20. Qe2 Bf6 {The powerful bishops
provide Black with full compensation for his structural drawbacks.}) (12. c5
{This aggressive continuation is aimed to break Black's pawn chain and develop an initiative on the kingside. However, as the practice proves, it only helps
Black to activate his minor pieces} Qc7 13. cxd6 Bxd6 14. Bg5 Bb7 {Black
reached a harmonious setup a-la Meran} (14... exd4 15. Bxf6 gxf6 {is a common
alternative, but I see no reason for accepting the damage of the kingside pawn
structure.}) 15. Nbd2 {This position was reached in Hindle, O-Hartoch, R
Birmingham 1963} ({After} 15. Nc3 exd4 16. e5 (16. Qxd4 c5 $15) 16... Nxe5 17.
Bxf6 Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3 dxc3 19. Qg4 g6 20. Bxc3 c5 {White didn't have much for
the pawn in Zdebskaja, N - Galojan, L Dresden 2008}) {At this moment there was
no reason for deviating from the most natural} 15... c5 $146 16. d5 c4 17. Bc2
Ne8 18. Be3 Bc5 {with great prospects on the queenside. White's d5-passer is
blocked, while his pieces are rather passive.}) (12. Qc2 {This move is known
since 70'es, and it was employed by such great players like Tal, Geller, Timman
and others. White waits for 12...Bb7 and hopes to get an improved version of
12. Nc3 b4 line.} Bb7 13. Nc3 (13. a3 {Like after 12.a3, Black feels free to
challenge the centre with} exd4 14. Nxd4 bxc4 15. Bxc4 d5 16. exd5 cxd5 17. Ba2
Rc8 18. Nc3 Ne4 19. Be3 Bf6 {Black's active piece play fully compensates for
the isolated pawn.}) 13... exd4 $1 {At his turn, now Black is better prepared
for releasing the tension in the centre.} ({Indeed, after} 13... b4 14. Na4 c5
15. d5 Nh5 16. Qd1 Nf4 17. Bc2 Ng6 18. b3 {Black was suffering from the
passive Bb7 in Lu, S -Ding, L Taizhou 2015}) 14. Nxd4 b4 15. Na4 c5 16. Nf5 {
Usually, the presence of Nf5 is quite annoying for Black in Ruy Lopez.
However, in this case, the other pieces do not join the attack.} Re8 17. Bf4 ({
The move} 17. f3 {is not promising.} Bf8 18. Bg5 Bc6 19. Rad1 Qc7 20. Qd2 Qa5 {
The poor location of Na4 forced White to search for perpetual:} 21. Bxf6
Nxf6 22. Qg5 Bxa4 23. Nh6+ {Vitolins,E - Dos Santos,M corr 2012}) 17... Bf8 18.
f3 {Provoking this move is Black's undeniable achievement.} Ne5 19. Rad1 Qc7
20. Bg5 (20. Qd2 Rad8 21. Bg5 Re6 22. Ne3 Be7 {Black had an excellent play
along the dark squares in Jacobsen, J - Koch, H GER email 2010}) 20... Re6 21.
Ne3 {This position was reached in Shirov, A - Dragun, K Czech Republic 2016 At
this moment Black could have exploited the lack of harmony in White's setup by
means of} Nh5 $1 22. f4 ({Hardly better is} 22. Rf1 h6 23. Bh4 g5 24. Bf2 Bg7
$15 {Black has full control over dark squares.}) 22... h6 23. Nd5 (23. f5 $2
hxg5 24. fxe6 fxe6 {is just strategically lost for White.}) 23... Bxd5 24. exd5
Rg6 25. Qe2 hxg5 26. fxe5 Rh6 {Black has better prospects in view of awful
Na4.}) (12. Nbd2 {In comparison to 12.Nc3 this move looks less pretending
since White has less control over the centre. Still, it was played by strong
players and we should consider it seriously} Bb7 13. a4 {The most consistent -
White massively attack the opponent's weak point - the b5-pawn.} ({After} 13.
Bc2 Re8 14. b3 exd4 15. Nxd4 Bf8 16. Bb2 g6 {Black reaches the flexible setup
and is ready to put strong pressure on the e4.} 17. b4 Rc8 18. N4f3 c5 {
White faced some problems in Smirin, I - Inarkiev, E Poikovsky 2015}) 13... Qc7
14. Bc2 {The natural play from both sides led to this interesting position in
Pavlidis, A - Diermair, A Hersonissos 2017 Now Black should have maintained the
tension by means of} Rfe8 $146 15. axb5 ({The alternatives are hardly more
promising:} 15. b3 exd4 16. Nxd4 b4 17. Nf5 Bf8 18. Bb2 g6 19. Ne3 Bg7 $132) (
15. b4 bxc4 16. Nxc4 exd4 17. Nxd4 d5 $132) 15... axb5 16. Rxa8 Rxa8 17. cxb5
cxb5 18. Nb3 Rc8 19. Bd3 d5 $1 {This thematic break comes on time and allows
Black to make use of his better development - the c1-bishop is still on its
initial spot.} 20. exd5 e4 21. Bxe4 Nxe4 22. Rxe4 Bd6 {Black has full
compensation for the pawn.}) 12... exd4 {Indeed, it makes sense to open up the
position, so White's delay with development might tell.} 13. Nxd4 Ne5 {The
knight enters the centre with a great effect. As a result, it forces White to
release the tension in the centre.} 14. cxb5 axb5 {Undoubtedly, the change of
the pawn structure favours Black. However, White hopes to exploit the weakness
of c6.} 15. Bf4 ({The more aggressive} 15. f4 Nc4 16. Nc3 {, as in Sutovsky, E
- Bologan, V Poikovsky 2015 exposes the diagonal a7-g1 and makes the e4-pawn
somewhat vulnerable. This might tell in the following case:} (16. Nxc6 Qb6+ 17.
Nd4 d5 {with the idea of ...Bc5 which gives Black an excellent play.}) 16...
Bd7 $146 {This is better} ({than} 16... d5 {, as in Sutovsky,E - Bologan,V
Poikovsky 2015}) 17. Bxc4 (17. Nf3 Qb6+ 18. Kh2 Rfe8 19. e5 Nd5 20. Nxd5 cxd5
21. Qxd5 Bc6 $132) 17... bxc4 18. Qe2 Qb6 19. Be3 c5 20. Nf3 Bc6 21. Qxc4 Qb7 {
The pressure along the diagonal a1-h8 offers Black excellent counterplay.}) (
15. Be3 Bd7 16. Nc3 Re8 17. Qe2 Bf8 {was fine for Black in Antolak, J -
Shuvalova,P Germany GER 2018}) 15... Qb6 {This is the most active way of
