Nc5 {Black's active piece play fully compensates the relatively weak d6-pawn.
Vutov,M - Arnaudov,P Bankia 2013}) 13... c4 14. Bc2 Nc5 15. Nf1 {Maintaining
the tension is White's best attempt to fight for the initiative.} ({Or} 15. axb5
axb5 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. b4 cxb3 18. Nxb3 Nxb3 19. Bxb3 Bc8 {The pawns on c3 and
b5 were equally weak in Luther, T - Henrichs, T Bad Koenigshofen 2007}) ({
Toothless is} 15. a5 g6 16. b4 cxb3 17. Nxb3 Rc8 {Black has an easy play due to
the pressure on the c3 in Polgar, J - Navara, D Prague 2010}) 15... Qc7 16. Ng3
Rfb8 {The main merit of this move is making f8 vacant for the bishop. Also,
Bb7-c8 would keep Black's rooks connected.} (16... g6 {is another common move,
but this time the presence of Nf5 wouldn't bother Black.}) 17. Nf5 Bf8 18. Bg5
({Hardly better is} 18. Qe2 Bc8 19. g4 Bd7 20. axb5 axb5 21. Bg5 Ne8 22. Nd2
Ra7 23. Be3 Rba8 24. Rxa7 Rxa7 {Black took the control over the a-file and
soon managed to seize the initiative in Polgar, J - Kasparov, G Internet 2000})
18... Ne8 19. Nd2 Bc8 20. g4 {We have been following the game Safarli, E -
Lagno, K Moscow 2007 Now my natural improvement is} Bd7 $146 21. axb5 axb5 $11 {
, and Black would soon force favourable exchanges along the a-file.} *

