{[%evp 0,44,17,17,17,25,4,22,25,4,4,-19,19,-1,4,3,16,-14,-14,-21,24,6,-6,9,0,
-1,30,17,16,7,7,14,32,1,8,15,8,2,14,7,-4,15,-6,-6,5,6,26]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4
Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. b3 {This natural move is known since 1960'es.
Apart from preparing the fianchetto, White also aims at building up a strong
pawn centre with d4-d5, followed by c3-c4.} Bf8 14. d5 {An ambitious move,
that secures White a solid space advantage. On the other hand, releasing the
tension makes it easier for Black to develop his counter-play on the queenside.
} (14. a4 {transposes to 13.a4, sidelines.}) ({The other consistent
continuation is} 14. Bb2 g6 15. a4 ({Dubious is} 15. d5 $6 c6 16. c4 Qc7 17.
Rc1 b4 18. Nf1 Bh6 {That's the point! Since the b2-bishop is misplaced Black's
bishop takes control over c1-h6 diagonal.} 19. Ra1 cxd5 20. cxd5 Rac8 $15 {
White was doomed to passive defence in Cabrera Trujillo, J - Solomon, K Budapest
2010}) 15... Nh5 $1 {The same approach as in 13.a4 lines - the knight heads on
f4, and then on e6 in order to put more pressure on the d4.} 16. Bd3 (16. c4 {
was seen in Romanishin, O - Petrosian, Moscow 1972 Now the natural} b4 $1 17. d5
a5 {would have offered Black an excellent play due to the control over the
c5-spot.}) 16... Nf4 17. Bf1 c6 18. g3 (18. Qc2 Qc7 {transposes to Gashimov -
McShane, from 13.a4}) 18... Ne6 19. b4 Qc7 20. Nb3 Nb6 21. axb5 ({Too passive
is} 21. a5 $6 Nc4 22. Bc1 Bg7 $15) 21... axb5 22. Qc2 Nc4 {Black had an
excellent play in Macovei,A - Miron,L Iasi 2016}) 14... c6 15. c4 Qc7 {The
lack of harmony in White's camp makes it difficult to cover the c2-bishop. So,
Black starts putting pressure along the c-file.} 16. Nf1 {The most natural way
of handling the position. White is planning to relocate his knight on e3 in
order to cover the c2-bishop and make d2 vacant for his bishop.} (16. a4 {
was played once by Anatoly Karpov and definitely has to be mentioned} bxc4 17.
bxc4 a5 $1 {As usual, Black fixes the weak a4-pawn and frees the a6-square for
his bishop.} 18. Nb3 Ba6 19. Bd3 ({Inferior is} 19. dxc6 $6 Qxc6 20. Nxa5 Qc7
21. Bd2 Nc5 22. Re3 Bc8 {White lacked coordination in Firman,N - Maiorov,N
Lvov 2006.}) 19... Reb8 20. Ba3 g6 {In this complicated position, Black's
chances are by no means worse.}) 16... Rec8 17. Ne3 g6 {There is no need to
release the favourable tension on the queenside. At the moment, Black prepares
the activation of his dark-squared bishop.} 18. Bd2 ({The attempt to develop
an attack on the kingside isn't effective:} 18. Nh2 bxc4 19. bxc4 cxd5 20. cxd5
h5 {Now the h2-knight is out of play.} 21. Bd2 a5 22. Rc1 Qd8 23. Qf3 Ba6 24.
Nhf1 Bh6 {Black was better in Avotins,M - Rubinas,P ICCF email 2009}) 18... a5
$1 {The last prophylactic move.} 19. Rc1 ({In case of} 19. dxc6 Qxc6 20. cxb5
Qxb5 {the weak e4-pawn causes White serious problems.}) 19... bxc4 20. bxc4 Nc5
21. dxc6 Bxc6 22. Nd5 Qd8 {The natural play from both sides led to equal
position in Zapata,A - Bruzon Batista,L Havana 2003} *

