{[%evp 0,36,40,25,25,25,22,9,25,4,6,17,23,3,3,3,16,-11,-10,-11,11,10,-3,17,11,
10,16,-4,20,38,38,41,23,-7,24,-6,-11,-14,-9]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4.
Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2
Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. b4 Bf8 14. Bb2 {This setup was tried by such great players
like Tal, Shirov and others. Still, by deviating from a2-a4, White heavily
limits his active possibilities on the queenside and makes it easier for Black
to reach equality.} (14. a4 {trasposes to 13.a4}) 14... Nb6 {The knight is
perfectly hosted on b6, covering both a4 and c4.} 15. a3 ({The ambitious} 15.
Rc1 Nfd7 16. c4 bxc4 17. a4 exd4 18. Bxd4 {, as in Firat, B - Ipatov, A Kocaeli
2014 can be well met by} Nf6 $146 19. a5 Nbd7 {, and then White would be
forced to exchange his powerful dark-squared bishop in order to regain the pawn
} 20. Bxf6 Nxf6 21. Ba4 Re7 22. Rxc4 Rb8 {Black has a great play.}) 15... Nfd7
{The other knight comes to make c7-c5 more effective.} 16. Rc1 ({After} 16. Qe2
Rc8 17. c4 bxc4 18. Nxc4 exd4 19. Nxb6 cxb6 {Draw was agreed in Hjorth, J -
Mamrukov, D ICCF email 2013 Indeed, Black doesn't have any problems. For
instance,} 20. Bxd4 Nf6 21. Bxf6 Qxf6 {, and White has to take care of
equalizing.}) 16... c5 {This position occurred in Thipsay - Prasad, Pune 2004.
Undoubtedly, the only challenging reaction from White's side would be} 17. bxc5
dxc5 18. d5 c4 $15 {The poor b2-bishop makes White's position rather passive
while f7-f5 is to follow soon.} *

