{[%evp 0,46,40,25,25,25,22,22,17,6,8,8,19,3,3,3,21,-11,-10,-10,25,-5,12,11,11,
-1,16,-17,28,27,39,26,41,43,41,35,67,17,34,16,33,-2,13,2,-10,-6,-6,-8,-14]} 1.
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O
9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. a4 Bf8 14. Bd3 {The main
continuation. By attacking b5, White forces Black to lock the b7-bishop. In
this way, the e4-pawn would be no longer under pressure.} c6 15. b3 {The most
common and flexible continuation. White's dark-squared bishop might be placed
either on b2 or a3, while c3-c4 break is still in the air.} (15. b4 {We are
already familiar with this way of expansion.} Nb6 {Unlike the positions that
arise after 15.b3, Black can force White to immediately release the tension on
the queenside.} 16. axb5 ({In case of} 16. a5 Nbd7 17. Bb2 {Black might force
favorable complications by means of} exd4 $1 18. cxd4 c5 19. bxc5 dxc5 20. e5
Nd5 21. h4 h6 22. Bb1 Nb4 23. Bf5 c4 {The strong queenside passers put White
under serious pressure in Morcin,T - Lizorkina,V LSS email 2011.}) 16... axb5
17. Rxa8 Qxa8 18. Nb3 h6 {A decent prophylactic move that restricts the
mobility of the c1-bishop.} 19. Na5 ({Equally good is} 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. Be3
Na4 21. Qc2 Bc8 22. Ra1 Qb8 23. Na5 Bd7 {Shankland,S - Kamsky,G Saint Louis
2014}) 19... Bc8 20. Qc2 ({White achieves nothing special after} 20. Be3 exd4
21. Bxd4 Nbd7 22. Qd2 Ne5 $11) 20... Bd7 21. Bd2 {We have been following the
game Pruijssers,R - Zoler,D Dieren 2010 Now I mostly like} c5 $146 22. d5 Rc8
23. Qb2 Rc7 24. Ra1 Ra7 {The misplaced a5-knight might cause White some
problems in the long run.}) 15... Qc7 (15... g6 {is the most common move, but
there seems to be nothing wrong with connecting the rooks at once.}) 16. Bb2 (
16. Ba3 {looks somewhat more active, but Black can employ the same plan:} g6
17. Qc2 Nh5 $1 {The knight heads on e6} 18. Bf1 (18. g3 Ng7 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20.
Nxe5 dxe5 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 {was absolutely equal in Dabija, M - Ward, A ICCF email
2009}) 18... Nf4 19. g3 Ne6 {Since b3 isn't vacant for the d2-knight, the
pressure on d4 feels annoying now.} 20. Bb2 Bg7 21. b4 {This was Brodsky, M -
Aleksandrov, A Kherson 1991 At this moment Black could have seized the
initiative by means of} exd4 $1 $146 22. cxd4 Nb6 23. axb5 (23. a5 Na4 $36)
23... cxb5 24. Qxc7 Nxc7 25. Rac1 Rac8 $15) (16. Qc2 {is another common move,
but after} g6 {White takes the game into usual paths with} 17. Bb2 ({or} 17.
Ba3)) 16... g6 17. Qc2 {This move makes White's setup more harmonious} ({
Sometimes, White leaves the queen on its initial spot with} 17. Bf1 {, but
after} Nh5 {there is hardly a better alternative anyway. For instance,} 18. b4
Nf4 19. Qb3 d5 $1 {This thematic break comes on time.} 20. g3 Nh5 21. exd5 bxa4
22. Qxa4 exd4 23. dxc6 ({In case of} 23. Nxd4 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 cxd5 25. Bg2 Nhf6 {
Black's active piece play fully compensates for the weak d5-pawn.}) 23... Bxc6
{Black didn't have problems in Romanov, R-Weber, K ICCF email 2011}) 17... Nh5 $1
{It makes sense to keep the f8-bishop on its initial spot for a while.} ({
Less precise is} 17... Bg7 18. c4 $1 bxc4 (18... bxa4 19. c5 axb3 20. Nxb3 {
also offers White promising play for the pawn.}) 19. Bxc4 exd4 20. Bxd4 c5 21.
Bc3 {, and White's chances are preferable.}) 18. Bf1 ({In comparison to the
above-mentioned note,} 18. c4 {is well met by} bxa4 $1 19. c5 {This took place
in Grib,R - Paprocki,J Suwalki POL 2018} (19. Rxa4 exd4 20. Bxd4 Nf4 21. Bf1 c5
22. Ba1 Ne6 {offers Black an excellent play along the dark squares.}) {Now
Black should have played} 19... axb3 20. Nxb3 exd4 21. cxd6 Bxd6 22. Bxd4 c5 {
, and there is nothing to worry about.}) ({The} 18. g3 {is not dangerous.} Ng7
19. Kh2 Rac8 20. Qb1 Qb6 $11 {Visser,H - Vishnu,P Vlissingen 2014}) 18... Nf4
19. c4 {The most ambitious.} ({Instead, the quiet} 19. g3 Ne6 20. h4 {leads to
a long strategic struggle where Black's chances are not worse. For instance,}
Bg7 21. Bh3 Rad8 22. axb5 {This was Clarke,B - Friedel,J Internet 2018 Now my
natural improvement is} axb5 $146 23. h5 Bc8 24. hxg6 hxg6 $11) 19... bxa4 20.
Rxa4 exd4 21. g3 ({Worse is} 21. Nxd4 c5 22. N4f3 Ne6 23. g3 Ne5 $15 {Migot,T
- Ghosh,D Riga 2017}) 21... Ne6 22. Nxd4 Nec5 23. Raa1 a5 $11 {The pressure on
b3 and e4 fully compensated the structural drawbacks in Gashimov,V - McShane,L
Novi Sad 2009} *

