{[%evp 0,50,40,25,25,25,22,17,41,16,10,11,27,3,5,5,16,-10,-11,-11,11,12,16,16,
16,3,16,7,13,-20,10,-65,5,-80,-1,28,42,27,21,21,24,28,8,22,22,17,37,23,28,-2,1,
21,23]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6
8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Bg5 {
This move was first seen in 1960, but it became popular mainly due to the
brilliant Vugar Gashimov, who passed away 5 years ago. In comparison to 14.Ng3,
the bishop can be retreated on h4, so pinning the f6-knight is more effective
now. However, as the practice proves, the e4-pawn is under strong pressure.
That is why in some cases White would be forced to exchange it.} h6 15. Bh4 g6
{As usual, this advance limits White's attacking potential and makes Black's
setup more harmonious.} 16. a4 ({Releasing the tension in the centre hardly
offers much either:} 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. N3h2 Be7 $1 {For some reason, this
natural move is a rare guest in practice.} ({At the same time, the most common
} 17... Bg7 18. Qf3 {leads to a somewhat passive position, when the pin along
h4-d8 diagonal causes Black certain problems.}) 18. Qf3 ({Perhaps, better is} 
18. Qd2 Kg7 19. Rad1 Nb6 {, but even then Black manages to consolidate and
reach a comfortable position:} 20. Qe2 Qc8 21. Qf3 Nc4 22. b3 Nd6 $11) 18...
Nh5 $1 {The exchange of the bishops yields Black access to the f4-spot.} 19.
Bb3 {Bick,G - Rohan,A Berkeley 2018} ({The quiet} 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Rad1 Rad8 {
still offers Black a somewhat better position.}) 19... Bxh4 20. Qxf7+ Kh8 21.
Qxg6 Qf6 22. Qxh5 Bxf2+ 23. Kh1 Bxe1 24. Rxe1 Qg5 $15) ({The attempt to
increase the pressure on f6 isn't very effective:} 16. N1h2 Bg7 17. dxe5 ({
The immediate} 17. Ng4 {runs into} exd4 $1 18. cxd4 Qc8 19. Nxf6+ Nxf6 {
The strong pressure on e4 forces White to give the dark-squared bishop away.}
20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. e5 Bg7 {Black was slightly better in Quesada Perez,Y -
Molner,M Arlington 2013}) 17... dxe5 18. Ng4 Qe7 $1 {It turns out, that Black
can avoid the pin without spoiling the pawn structure.} ({Less precise is} 
18... g5 $6 19. Bg3 Nxg4 20. hxg4 Qe7 21. a4 c5 22. Nd2 Nf6 23. Nf1 Qe6 24. f3
{The weak f5-square in Black's camp started to tell in Gashimov,V - Navara,D
Reggio Emilia 2011}) 19. Qd2 g5 $1 {Now, this move is well-timed since d2
isn't available for White's knight.} 20. Nxf6+ (20. Bg3 Rad8 21. Qe3 Nh5 {
is fine for Black - none of knights reaches f5.}) 20... Nxf6 21. Bg3 Nh5 {
Black had an excellent play in Gashimov,V - Svidler,P Astrakhan 2010}) (16.
N3d2 c6 ({Instead,} 16... Bg7 17. d5 c6 18. c4 {, as was tested in a few games
offers White definite space advantage when the b7-bishop is locked for a
while.}) 17. Qf3 $6 ({More to the point was} 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Qf3 Bg7 19. Ne3
Qc7 $11) 17... Bg7 18. Ne3 Qb6 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 {Black was better in Sutovsky, E -
Vitiugov,N Caleta 2017}) 16... Bg7 17. d5 Qb8 $1 {The similar flexible way of
defending the d6 can be seen in 15.a4 and some more lines of Breyer.} 18. Ne3 (
{Traditionally,} 18. b3 c6 19. c4 bxc4 20. bxc4 a5 $1 {offers Black an
excellent play along the dark squares.}) 18... c6 19. dxc6 Bxc6 20. axb5 axb5
21. Rxa8 Bxa8 22. Nd2 {This position was reached in Vachier Lagrave, M -
Buhmann, R Dortmund 2016. At this moment, Black should have played} Nh5 $146 23.
f3 Nf4 24. Ndf1 Bf6 25. Bf2 Rd8 {,reaching a comfortable position. The d6-d5
break is to follow soon.} *

