{[%evp 0,52,40,25,22,22,22,4,28,9,3,-2,16,5,5,5,16,-22,-23,-24,12,12,16,0,16,8,
8,5,25,23,24,5,14,27,29,27,27,12,25,17,29,30,30,30,46,34,25,15,10,18,2,25,45,
56,22]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6.
Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13.
Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 {This is White's second most popular choice
according to statistics. At some point, this move even became the main
preference of the top players. In comparison to 15.a4, White isn't focused on
attacking the b5-pawn. He mainly aims to seize more space in the centre by
advancing d4-d5 and c3-c4.} a5 $5 {This move was introduced in 2007 by one of
the leading Breyer experts Gata Kamsky. Black leaves the dark-squared bishop
on its initial spot for a while, so the d6-pawn remains protected. Moreover,
the potential b5-b4 advance might undermine White's control of d4 and offer
Black good prospects on the queenside.} ({In my opinion, the following
high-level game illustrates the strategic danger of Black's position if he
lets White to lock the centre:} 15... Bg7 16. d5 Qe7 {Black connects the rooks
and makes c7-c6 possible.} (16... c6 $6 17. dxc6 Bxc6 18. Qxd6 {leaves Black
with no adequate compensation for the pawn.}) (16... Nb6 $5 {is another common
response. Even here, however, Peter managed to claim superiority after} 17. Rb1
$1 c6 18. c4 Qc7 19. Bd3 Nfd7 20. Be3 $14 {Leko,P - Beliavsky,A Bled 2002}) 17.
c4 c6 18. Be3 Rec8 19. Rc1 a5 {The same approach worked well for Black in
similar positions that arise after 15.a4. However, in this situation White can
interrupt Black's plan.} 20. Qd2 bxc4 21. bxc4 cxd5 ({In particular, the
typical counterattacking move} 21... Ba6 {is now well met by} 22. Ba4 $1 cxd5
23. cxd5 {, and White is firmly in control.}) 22. cxd5 Nc5 23. Bd3 {Black is
left with a passive bishop on b7 and was eventually outplayed in Leko, P -
Short, N Wijk aan Zee 2005.}) 16. a4 {This is the most challenging reply -
White provokes his opponent to push b5-b4 so that the a4-pawn may become a
passer.} ({The prophylactic} 16. a3 d5 $1 {is well met by} 17. Bg5 {The only
way to fight for the initiative.} ({The timid} 17. dxe5 $6 dxe4 18. Nxe4 Nxe4
19. Bxe4 Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Nxe5 $15 {allows Black to seize the initiative.}) 17...
h6 {This move forces the favourable exchange of opponent's dark-squared bishop.}
18. Bxf6 ({Over-optimistic is} 18. Bh4 $6 g5 19. Nxg5 hxg5 20. Bxg5 exd4 21. e5
(21. cxd4 dxe4 22. Nxe4 Bg7 $17) 21... Rxe5 22. Rxe5 Nxe5 23. cxd4 Ng6 24. Qf3
Ra6 {leaves White no sufficient play for the piece.}) 18... Qxf6 19. exd5 exd4
20. Rxe8 (20. Nxd4 Rxe1+ 21. Qxe1 Bxd5 22. Nxb5 Qb6 23. c4 Bb7 $44 {also
provides Black with full compensation for the pawn due to the powerful
dark-squared bishop.}) (20. Ne4 $2 Rxe4 21. Bxe4 dxc3 $17 {is bad for White
who is paralyzed by the strong c3-pawn.}) 20... Rxe8 21. Nxd4 b4 22. axb4 axb4
{Black took full control over the dark squares. White doesn't pretend on
claiming superiority. Anand,V - Amin,B Batumi GEO 2018}) (16. Bd2 {isnot a
successful attempt to stop b5-b4:} b4 $1 17. cxb4 (17. Bd3 {is traditionally
met by} d5 $1 {when Black successfully solves his space problems:} 18. Qc2 c5
19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Rxe5 21. Bf4 Re6 $11 {Unander,M - Laane,E email 2008})
17... axb4 18. d5 ({Toothless is} 18. dxe5 dxe5 19. Bd3 Ba6 20. Bxa6 Rxa6 {
with pressure along the a-file.}) (18. Bxb4 $2 exd4 {leaves White in
inferior position since Black has control over the centre.}) 18... Qb8 $1 {
In this way, Black manages to maintain the material balance.} 19. Bxb4 Bxd5 20.
Bc3 Bb7 {Black had a comfortable play due to the control over the centre in
Haver,B - Haver,D Delft 2016}) ({In case of} 16. d5 c6 17. c4 {a6-a5 also
turns out to be a vital move. After} Nc5 18. Be3 bxc4 19. bxc4 Nfd7 20. Qd2 Qc7
{, Black is in time to regroup his pieces and start attacking the c4-pawn.
Kiran,M - Mohota,N Kolkata 2013}) ({Harmless is also} 16. Bd3 b4 17. cxb4 axb4
18. dxe5 {This was Smeets,J - Svidler,P Nice FRA 2010. Now it made sense to
maintain the pressure along the e-file:} Nxe5 $146 19. Nxe5 Rxe5 {with an
excellent play.}) 16... b4 17. cxb4 (17. c4 {isn't an improvement:} exd4 18.
Nxd4 Nc5 {The pressure on the e4 is so strong that White has nothing better
than exposing his king with} 19. f3 Nfd7 {Black has an excellent play along
the dark squares.}) 17... axb4 18. Bb2 ({In case of} 18. d5 c6 19. dxc6 Bxc6 {
the d6-d5 break would offer Black an easy play in the centre.}) (18. dxe5 {
Releasing the tension definitely suits Black, who's knight acquires access
to c5} dxe5 19. Bg5 (19. Bd3 $2 Nc5 $17) 19... h6 20. Bd2 ({After} 20. Be3 Nc5
21. Qc1 h5 22. Rd1 Qe7 {the e4-pawn is very vulnerable.}) 20... Ba6 21. Qc1 Kh7
22. Rd1 c5 23. Qb1 c4 {Black was fine in Dantas,R - Dard, M email 2008}) 18...
Bh6 {The bishop is perfectly placed on c1-h6 diagonal and makes it more
difficult for White to connect his rooks.} 19. dxe5 {Eventually, White finds
nothing better than simplifying the matters.} (19. Bd3 exd4 20. Nxd4 {, as in
Ganguly, S - Stefanova, A Caleta 2017 can be met by} c5 21. Nb5 Bf4 22. Qf3 Be5
23. Bxe5 Nxe5 24. Qe3 Nxd3 25. Qxd3 Re6 $132) 19... dxe5 20. Bd3 {The most
natural continuation - transferring the bishop on c4 would significantly
improve White's setup. However, it also invites Black to activate his knight.}
(20. Qe2 {is hardly an improvement, as was illustrated in the following fresh
encounter:} Qe7 21. Bd3 Bf4 22. Bb5 Red8 23. Rad1 Nc5 24. Bc4 Rd6 $132 {
Both e4 and the b3 became targets for Black's knights in Adams, M - Amin, B
Astana KAZ 2019.}) 20... Nc5 21. Bb5 Qxd1 22. Raxd1 c6 23. Bc4 {Visually,
White's position looks better but Black's next move illustrates that the
b3-pawn is still a serious problem.} Nfd7 {The knight covers e5 and heads on
b6.} 24. Bc1 ({Hardly better is} 24. Re2 {, as in Shirov,A - Kamsky,G
Khanty-Mansiysk 2007. At this moment, Black could have played} Bf8 $5 $146 25.
Rc2 Bc8 26. Ng5 Re7 {when the weakness on b3 causes White definite problems.})
24... Bf4 25. Be3 Ba6 26. Bxa6 Rxa6 {The pressure on b3 offered Black a full
compensation for his inferior pawn structure in Zhigalko, S - Eljanov, P Kiev
2013.} *

