{[%evp 0,64,33,22,22,24,24,16,45,7,8,7,28,5,3,3,16,-8,-21,-13,16,16,16,10,20,
19,20,21,30,23,31,31,38,19,56,56,102,64,52,52,52,38,38,51,43,22,41,38,51,51,51,
51,60,17,17,24,27,17,23,8,3,0,10,6,53,37,40]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4.
Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2
Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. a4 {This is by far the most common
move in the position. By attacking the b5 White is trying to provoke c7-c6,
that would release the pressure on the e4 and make Black's setup rather
passive.} Bg7 {Now Black's setup is completed.} (15... c5 16. d5 c4 {is the
most popular alternative that leads to a long strategic struggle. In general,
White's play is based on opening the f-file with the well-timed f2-f4 break
while Black hopes to develop fast play on the queenside.}) 16. Bd3 {A
consistent continuation. White attacks the weak b5-pawn and invites the
opponent to show his cards.} (16. d5 Qb8 $1 {This is the most flexible way of
covering d6, so c7-c6 is now possible.} 17. b3 c6 18. c4 {White managed to
build up a strong pawns centre that is supposed to squeeze the opponent's
pieces. However, it turns out, that Black has a clear plan of counterattack
which mainly based on attacking the c4-pawn.} bxc4 19. bxc4 a5 {[%cal Gb7a6]
An important move that keeps White's light-squared bishop passive and secures
prepares ...Ba6.} 20. Rb1 (20. Ba3 {White achieves no advantage after} Bf8 21.
Ne2 Qc7 22. Nc3 Ba6 23. Bb3 Nc5 24. Bxc5 dxc5 {Shirov,A - Roiz,M Cala Mayor
2008}) (20. Be3 Qc7 21. Qd2 Ba6 22. Rac1 Nc5 23. Bxc5 dxc5 24. Red1 Rab8 {
was better for Black in Leitao, R - Kunte, Istanbul 2000}) 20... Qc7 21. Be3 Ba6
22. Bd3 Rab8 23. Qc2 $6 ({Better was} 23. Qd2 Bf8 24. dxc6 Qxc6 25. Qxa5 Rxb1
26. Rxb1 Ra8 {Even here, Black would manage to regain the pawn and equalize.})
23... Rec8 24. Rxb8 Rxb8 25. Rb1 Rb4 $1 {White was doomed to passive defence
and eventually lost in Bellia, F - Roiz, M Stockholm 2014}) (16. Bg5 h6 17. Bd2
Nb6 {transposes to 15.Bg5.}) 16... exd4 $5 {A relatively fresh idea. Once the
position opens, Black could benefit from completing development. Of course,
releasing the tension in the centre is connected with an obvious risk since it
increases White's attacking potential.} (16... c6 {is a solid alternative, but
that makes Black's position rather passive.}) 17. cxd4 c5 {Black must act
actively in order to justify his previous decision. Now White is invited to
grab the pawn.} 18. axb5 ({The ambitious} 18. d5 $6 c4 19. Bc2 b4 $15 {gives
Black too much freedom on the queenside, while the e4-pawn is under strong
pressure.}) ({Another considerable option is} 18. Bf4 $5 {which leads to a
very concrete play after} cxd4 19. Bxd6 Re6 $1 {It's important to free the e8
for the knight's retreat.} 20. e5 {The most ambitious choice.} ({Retreating
shouldn't bother Black:} 20. Ba3 Ne5 $1 21. Nxe5 Rxe5 22. f4 Re6 23. axb5 axb5
{White's centre is fragile now.}) ({Or} 20. Bf4 Nc5 21. axb5 axb5 22. Rxa8 Bxa8
23. Bxb5 Nfxe4 {with an excellent piece play.}) 20... Ne8 21. Be4 (21. axb5
Nxd6 22. exd6 Rxd6 23. Ne4 Rb6 24. bxa6 Bxa6 {is equal.}) 21... Nxd6 22. exd6
Nc5 23. Bxb7 Rxe1+ 24. Qxe1 Nxb7 25. axb5 a5 $1 $132 {The d6-passer would fall
while Black's d4-pawn is going to be strong enough.}) 18... axb5 19. Rxa8 Bxa8
20. dxc5 (20. Bxb5 {was never seen in practice yet. Indeed, it only leads to
simplifications after} cxd4 21. Nxd4 Nxe4 22. Nxe4 Rxe4 23. Nc6 ({Toothless is
also} 23. Rxe4 Bxe4 24. Bf1 Qb8 25. Nb5 d5 26. Nc3 Bxc3 27. bxc3 Qb1 $11) 23...
Qe8 24. Rxe4 Qxe4 25. Qxd6 Qe1+ 26. Bf1 Bxc6 27. Qxc6 Bd4 $11) 20... Nxc5 21.
Bxb5 Rf8 {A sad necessity since Black has to keep his queen protected. However,
White's central pawn is still under strong pressure.} 22. e5 ({Too passive is} 
22. Bd3 Qb8 23. Bc2 Re8 {when Black regains the pawn under favourable
circumstances.}) 22... dxe5 23. Qxd8 ({Interesting is} 23. Nxe5 $5 Qd5 24. Qxd5
Nxd5 25. Bc4 Re8 26. f4 {It looks like White managed to consolidate and
maintain his extra pawn,} (26. Nd3 Rxe1+ 27. Nxe1 {transposes to main line.}) {
but after} 26... Nd7 $1 27. Nd3 (27. Bb5 Bxe5 28. fxe5 Rxe5 29. Rd1 N7b6 30.
Bh6 f6 {is equal.}) 27... Rxe1+ 28. Nxe1 Nc5 29. b3 Nb6 {The activity of
Black's pieces should suffice for an easy draw.}) 23... Rxd8 24. Nxe5 Nd5 {
White is a pawn up, but the pressure along h8-a1 is very strong. Still, Black
has to play accurately in order to maintain his activity.} 25. Bc4 Re8 26. Nf3
(26. f4 {is covered in the above-mentioned note.}) 26... Rxe1+ 27. Nxe1 Nb6 $1
{Despite the exchange of rooks, White fails to activate his pieces and advance
the passer.} 28. Ba2 ({Harmless is} 28. b3 Nxc4 29. bxc4 Bb7 30. Be3 Ne6 31.
Nc2 f5 {The powerful bishops provided Black with full compensation for the
pawn in Hou Yifan - Vitiugov, N Belokurikha 2018.}) 28... Bd5 $1 {This move
gives Black access to the light squares b3 and d3.} 29. Bxd5 Nxd5 30. Ne2 f5
$1 $146 {This move is aimed at restricting the mobility of the e2-knight and
activating the king.} ({Instead, premature is} 30... Nb3 $6 31. Nd3 Nb6 32. Bf4
Nc4 33. Nec1 $16 {White managed to convert his extra pawn into a full point in
Stefansson,H - Kazhgaleyev,M Batumi 2018}) 31. g4 Kf7 32. gxf5 gxf5 $11 {
White cannot make any progress, so his extra pawn has a symbolic value.} *

