-42,-21,11,16,-8,-36,16,-24,89,74,64]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6
5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12.
Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. Bg5 {This natural developing move is
introduced in the middle of 1950'es. The main idea behind it is provoking the
somewhat weakening h7-h6. In this way, White would have better attacking
prospects.} h6 ({Too passive is} 15... Bg7 16. Qd2 Qe7 17. b3 c6 18. Rad1 Qf8
19. a4 Rad8 20. Qc1 h6 21. Be3 Kh7 22. b4 {White had a big space advantage and
eventually won in Karjakin, S - Kamsky, G Nice 2009}) 16. Bd2 {This isn't a
perfect spot for the bishop, but the pressure on e4 leaves no better choice.} (
{Dubious is} 16. Be3 $6 exd4 17. Bxd4 (17. cxd4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 {leaves
White with no adequate compensation.}) 17... c5 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. a4 b4 {
Black was better due to his powerful dark-squared bishop in Ameir, M - Amin, B,
Cairo 2015.}) 16... Bg7 17. Qc1 (17. a4 {As usual, the b5-pawn is a target.
However, in this case, it's difficult for White to extend initiative on the
queenside in view of awkward location of his pieces.} Nb6 $1 {It makes sense
to provoke White to release the tension or create weak spots in his camp.} 18.
b3 {This is the most common response.} (18. axb5 axb5 19. b3 (19. Bd3 {, as
was tried in Hou Yifan - Vitiugov, N Belokurikha 2018 can be naturally met by}
Nc4 $146 20. Rxa8 Qxa8 21. Bc1 exd4 22. Nxd4 c6 $132) 19... c5 {Now, when the
a-file is open, Black doesn't mind to let White lock the b7-bishop.} 20. d5 Qc7
21. Qe2 c4 22. b4 {This was Pichot, A - Cheparinov, I Doha 2016. At this moment,
it made sense to swap all the rooks:} Rxa1 $146 23. Rxa1 Ra8 24. Qd1 Qb8 $11) (
18. Qc1 Kh7 {transposes to 17.Qc1.}) 18... bxa4 19. bxa4 Nc4 20. Bc1 {
Naturally, White prefers to deviate from exchanging his dark-squared bishop.
On the flipside, now half of his pieces are placed on their initial spots, so
Black feels free to challenge the centre.} (20. Rb1 Bc6 21. Bd3 (21. Bc1 d5 22.
Nxe5 ({The more interesting try would be} 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Qd3 {, but even
then after} Ndb6 $1 24. a5 Nxa5 25. Nxe5 Bxe5 26. dxe5 Qxd3 27. Bxd3 Nac4 {
the a-passer offers Black a comfortable play.}) 22... Nxe5 23. dxe5 Nxe4 24.
Nxe4 dxe4 {Black was fine in Balogh,C - Banusz,T Slovakia 2016}) 21... Nxd2 22.
Nxd2 {This position took place in Saurabh,A - Ghosh,D Mumbai 2016.} Qd7 {
At this point, Black could have expolited the lack of dark-squared bishop in
opponent's camp by means of} 23. a5 d5 $1 {,forcing favorable simplifications:}
24. dxe5 Nxe4 25. Ndxe4 dxe4 26. Bxe4 Qxd1 27. Rbxd1 Bxe4 28. Rxe4 Rxe5 {
White has to struggle for a draw.}) 20... d5 $1 {This thematic break comes on
time.} 21. Bd3 ({More accurate seems} 21. dxe5 Nxe4 22. Bf4 ({Bad is} 22. Nxe4
$2 dxe4 23. Qxd8 Raxd8 24. Bxe4 Bxe4 25. Rxe4 Rd1+ 26. Re1 Rxe1+ 27. Nxe1 Rxe5
$17) 22... Nxe5 23. Nxe4 dxe4 24. Bxe4 Bxe4 25. Rxe4 Qxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Nxf3+ 27.
gxf3 Rxe4 28. fxe4 Bxc3 29. Bxc7 Re8 $11 {, and draw is the most probable
result.}) 21... dxe4 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Bxc4 Nd6 24. Ba2 exd4 25. Rxe8+ Qxe8 26.
cxd4 {We have been following the correspondence game Klausner,H - Laurent,C
ICCF email 2011. At this moment Black could have won the pawn:} Bxf3 $146 27.
Qxf3 Bxd4 28. Rb1 Qe1+ 29. Kh2 Qxf2 30. Qxf2 Bxf2 31. Bxh6 Re8 $15 {White's
bishops don't offer a full compensation here.}) 17... Kh7 18. h4 {The most
aggressive attempt to fight for the initiative.} (18. a4 Nb6 19. b3 (19. axb5
axb5 20. Rxa8 Qxa8 21. dxe5 dxe5 22. b3 Nc8 23. Nh2 Nd6 {Liepold,S - Lipok,C
Germany 2014}) 19... bxa4 20. bxa4 a5 21. dxe5 {This exchange mostly favours
Black. Now, Black has enough space he is already planning to occupy the
c5-square with the knight.} ({The somewhat awkward} 21. Qb1 {, as in Kovchan, A
- Vaibhav, S Dresden 2018 can be well met by} Ba6 $146 22. Bb3 Bc4 23. Qa2 Bxb3
24. Qxb3 Kg8 {, and Black has no problems.}) 21... dxe5 22. Bb3 Qe7 23. Be3
Nfd7 24. h4 $6 {White pushes too hard.} ({More to the point was} 24. Qc2 Rab8
25. Qa2 Rf8 {with mutual chances.}) 24... Ba6 25. h5 Nc4 26. Bxc4 Bxc4 {
Black was better in Yu, Y - Piorun, K Caleta 2017}) ({White has also tried} 18.
Nh2 $6 {The knight's manoeuvre seems slow and makes it possible for Black to
seize the initiative with} d5 $1 19. dxe5 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22.
